WEBVTT

00:04.520 --> 00:05.021
Testing. One, two, three. I guess you might as well 
just start out and you might as well just talk about

00:06.784 --> 00:12.074
death for a minute. I had the essay from the first 
time you ever saw a dead man. And I realized that you

00:19.869 --> 00:22.013
were a child. And death is a part of life out here, 
too. Very much. And let me tell you that I wasn't but

00:29.540 --> 00:40.554
18 years old when I was called on to come and help 
dress a corpse. To dress a, yeah. And you know,

00:42.797 --> 00:48.464
that's something that people don't touch their 
bodies anymore. They send them on. But I was 18

00:50.807 --> 00:53.410
years old. And Miss came back, called me, and she 
said, you're just as well to learn. You have to face

00:59.023 --> 01:01.966
it sooner or later. And I said, oh, I just don't 
believe it. She said, oh, yes, you can. And she

01:06.913 --> 01:10.378
sighed, and she put her hands on my shoulders. And 
she looked me straight in the eye. She says, honey,

01:13.642 --> 01:18.348
dead people don't hurt you. It's the live ones that 
give you trouble. So these have laid all of their

01:22.145 --> 01:37.405
troubles down, and the least we can do is to make it 
pleasant for them for their last minutes here on

01:22.145 --> 01:37.405
this earth. And she says, Do you know when you go 
take a bath how much better that you feel and how

01:37.745 --> 01:49.120
much you really enjoy it? I said, Yes. She said, 
Well, when we wash all of this earthly

01:51.136 --> 02:13.279
feeding off of this body and put it in God's hands, 
we've done one of the greatest things that you can

01:51.136 --> 02:13.279
do for humanity. and I thought, I've never heard 
anyone express it like that. She said, that's the

02:22.208 --> 02:30.237
last respects that you can pay that person and put 
them in God's care. So you washed the body. So I

02:33.881 --> 02:42.490
washed the body, and I will never forget it if I live 
to be a million years old. That was a big chore. But

02:44.691 --> 02:51.276
then when she said, and you turn it over to God, and 
it's in his care. It's clean. She says, when the

02:52.738 --> 02:59.523
baby comes, you wash it with earthly water. Wash it 
in earthly water and return it to God who gave it. No

03:06.369 --> 03:08.431
one had ever talked to me like that. No one had ever 
said anything to me like that. So I have, I think, I

03:12.608 --> 03:22.906
thought that that was one of the sweetest ways to 
learn that ever was. It is. It was hard. I bet it was.

03:29.888 --> 03:32.031
And I do understand. I mean, I know, too, that 
there's a kindness in a death. Sure. That doesn't

03:38.018 --> 03:41.042
show up at any other time in this country. No. But 
the day we're born, there's a time set aside for our

03:42.124 --> 03:48.171
deaths. And regardless of what comes, it's going 
to be there. It's going to be there. And... God has a

03:54.880 --> 03:59.065
purpose for all of us. And we have a job to do. It may 
take us a long time to find it and to fly right to get

04:03.030 --> 04:09.657
it. But we have it, and we'll do it. And you said you 
believe that your purpose in life, that you still

04:13.782 --> 04:20.951
have purpose. I remember, I'm going to go back to 
the time that I met you, Because that's of a very

04:25.357 --> 04:28.983
important value to me. And that is the time that you 
had that massive heart attack and you were giving

04:30.465 --> 04:36.155
up. And I remember, I remember that you just made a 
decision. I hope I played a role in it. I like to

04:45.450 --> 04:46.812
think that I did. You sure did. And you, of course, 
have fulfilled the purpose of my life since. And

04:56.282 --> 04:59.076
I'm glad that you decided not To give up working on 
life and helping other people, because that's

05:00.018 --> 05:04.964
what you've done. You know, I really thought that 
my day's work was over. I did, too. I didn't know. I

05:12.853 --> 05:13.794
was scared. I really did. I really thought, well, 
this is the end. I can't make a comeback now. I'm too

05:20.221 --> 05:20.882
old. Yeah. Well, I think you can... My grandfather 
always said, hold to the end of the road. Hold to the

05:30.336 --> 05:31.938
end of the road. Never leave it shabby.

05:36.724 --> 05:37.225
All right. I didn't hold to the end of the road. 
There was something left for me to do. Now, what it

05:45.756 --> 05:47.338
is right now, I actually believe this with all my 
heart. And I believe it stronger today than I've

05:51.049 --> 06:02.847
ever believed it before, is helping little folks 
like I help today. Having those three little

06:03.468 --> 06:12.342
children to come, and actually the first time in 
their life to know what they were doing. To me, that

06:12.362 --> 06:15.587
is worth... A lifetime. Now, to get out here and for 
praise for the public, I wouldn't give you two

06:18.156 --> 06:26.235
cents and a half. But God knows what I was doing. And 
he knew I was working to make better children. And

06:32.881 --> 06:35.225
he knows what I do. Now, Ava, I know, I just, I think 
above race, creed, or color, it doesn't matter to

06:36.326 --> 06:43.217
you. I don't. It don't matter one bit. You have such 
a value to go on and to do that kind of work in this

06:45.400 --> 06:50.588
world. I've watched you do it. And it stems from 
that belief that you do row to the end of the, you

06:51.630 --> 06:56.938
know, the hole to the end of the rope. The end of the 
rope. And you do what has to be done. That's true.

07:02.885 --> 07:04.046
There was a little German. There was a little, 
well. Yeah, from Guatemala, you said? Guatemala.

07:11.795 --> 07:11.935
Uh-huh. And then this other little boy was born in 
the Yucatan. Yeah. He was from Guatemala, too.

07:24.949 --> 07:26.350
Yeah, somewhere down there. Yeah. All right. Now 
they're all different. And they've come up under

07:31.845 --> 07:34.709
different environments. And all together 
different ways of life.

07:41.897 --> 07:44.340
You didn't see any difference shown in those 
children. No, they were all children. They were

07:46.303 --> 07:47.684
all children to me. They were all God's children. 
And I was put here to help them. Well, like I see on

07:56.169 --> 08:01.778
that wall, I see the certificate of a tree that's 
been planted. And I'm going to get that down and

08:02.800 --> 08:08.109
read it right now because I know what it says, okay? 
I just love it. Because it's the victory forest in

08:11.684 --> 08:15.569
Jerusalem, right? That's right. And that's in 
honor of a great teacher, Ms. Ava Johnson Cox, from

08:17.591 --> 08:23.879
a thankful student. That's Eileen Balinski. 
That's pretty terrific. Not many. How many people

08:31.028 --> 08:35.253
do you know that have a tree planted? Well, I don't. 
You don't know too many. No, uh-uh. You don't, and

08:42.650 --> 08:45.053
that's really nice. Nice? Yeah, it's beautiful. 
To me, it's one of the greatest things that ever

08:49.357 --> 08:52.981
happened. Yeah, everything.

08:59.108 --> 09:09.619
I don't want

08:59.108 --> 09:09.619
people, when I die, to get up and say, oh, she was a 
wonderful person, she did this, she did that. All I

09:10.308 --> 09:15.012
want that minister to say, this woman lived. And 
when I say lived, she lived every day to the fullest

09:16.994 --> 09:23.840
extent. She gave her all, regardless of whatever 
it was she had to do. And I do. I put out every ounce of

09:31.266 --> 09:38.293
energy that's in my body for whatever I've got to do 
that day. And hope that I have another day coming to

09:39.451 --> 09:44.399
do. This one is the Texas Department of Aid on Aging 
Certificate of Appreciation to Ava Johnson Cox

09:44.419 --> 09:56.499
for volunteer service to older Texans. And that's 
signed by the governor. And a Republican at that.

10:00.826 --> 10:01.647
Yeah, I noticed that. I will have to say Clements 
signed it. We'll excuse that. But that's a grant.

10:08.537 --> 10:11.581
And that's Augusta Lucia? How do you say that? 
Augusta Lucia, Jr. And who is? She's the Hebrew

10:17.049 --> 10:18.451
girl. Is she? Yeah. Uh-huh. The chairman or 
president of the Texas Department on Aging?

10:30.397 --> 10:32.499
And you feel proud of things like that, Saban. 
Well, that's what I say. You said I had no feeling of

10:33.820 --> 10:38.184
class, color, or creed, and I don't. I know. You 
don't. You really don't. Well, I go back and, you

10:40.626 --> 10:43.088
know, I do. Just look at Armando yesterday. I know. 
Just as thrilled to see him come out, put his arms

10:45.710 --> 10:49.734
around me and kiss me. I know. Just as good a Mexican 
as ever lived. That's right. A question, too, I

10:54.078 --> 11:00.403
want to ask you here, because, again, every now and 
then, you know, we have to refer to the to Lyndon

