24:12.802 --> 24:19.953
or they thought it was out for a couple of days. But I 
know that the average person that I would talk to

24:21.095 --> 24:29.188
don't know what spunk wood is. But we have it in this 
country. And spunk wood is. And spunk wood kept

24:34.758 --> 24:43.972
burning just barely a little at a time, just enough 
to keep it warm. Then the wind changed and blew this

24:44.272 --> 24:49.320
spunk wood, as we call it, into grass then it got 
started and away it went and we certainly had a

24:50.228 --> 25:14.937
grass fire here that destroyed thousands and 
thousands of acres and fences but when I lived on

24:50.228 --> 25:14.937
the ranch and this is the first time and I've been 
living here since 1912

25:16.182 --> 25:25.555
And this is the first time that I've ever seen a fire 
that lingered as long as this one here. Yeah, I

25:25.575 --> 25:26.476
heard about it. And it was bad. But people, when you 
talk to them about spunk wood, they laugh at you.

25:34.166 --> 25:41.015
But it's just old, rotten wood that really hasn't 
all decayed. And...

25:45.697 --> 25:53.247
But it has enough life in it that when it is fired, it 
stays alive. It stays alive and alive and alive.

25:56.532 --> 25:58.214
Almost like peach bogs. Absolutely. And it is the 
hardest stuff in the world to put out. And that's

26:02.319 --> 26:05.123
exactly what happened. Well, I know that the 
pioneers talk about seeing these fires come and

26:05.322 --> 26:19.197
that settlers here fought and fought and fought 
because these things just swept the Great Plains

26:05.322 --> 26:19.197
for years. Sure they did. I have my grandmother's 
diary here and up there on the old ranch. It says

26:26.145 --> 26:32.292
that the grass was up to the horse's stomach. 
