26:34.500 --> 26:45.336
place up there because it was a spring and it was 
sub-irrigated all the way down and all around that

26:45.637 --> 26:55.557
40 acres that we sold to the park was all 
sub-irrigated from that spring. And when we dug

26:56.319 --> 27:06.700
that spring out in 1926,

26:56.319 --> 27:06.700
we dug up many, many bones of cattle. Oh, I mean of 
cows and horses and mules. We knew what kind of

27:11.413 --> 27:15.840
bones they were because naturally we had seen 
them. And lots of animals. What I mean by that, fox

27:17.963 --> 27:22.029
and squirrel. You can tell a red bone where it comes 
from, what type of animal it is in a red bone. Now,

27:29.540 --> 27:34.948
you may not understand what I mean by red bone 
animals. But they do have a red bone. A squirrel is a

27:38.724 --> 27:40.305
red bone animal. Oh, really? That's right, if you 
don't believe me. Well, that's true. And that's

27:46.932 --> 27:54.400
the thing that I don't understand about people 
today. But I guess it's because they have never

27:54.840 --> 28:00.666
been told. No, they've never been told. And 
they've never had to know these things. But I was

28:07.231 --> 28:12.603
told when I was quite small about red bone animals. 
In fact, they didn't insist that you eat them. Oh,

28:18.356 --> 28:19.299
really? That's right. But during the Hoover days, 
I ate plenty of red bone animals. A lot of squirrel?

28:27.295 --> 28:28.457
A lot of squirrel. You betcha. I have too, I know. 
And they'll tell you that jackrabbits are no good.

28:33.823 --> 28:36.347
